A black box in your car?
While U.S. road network planners have a hard time finding the money needed to repair the decaying highway infrastructure, many people see a solution in the form of a small black box that sits above your car’s dashboard.
The planes, which record every mile driven by a motorist and pass on information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government offices to reshape the outdated funding system of major U.S. roads.
The generally uninteresting sector of major axis planning has suddenly sparked a lively debate and turbulent alliances.
The libertarians have joined environmental groups to pressure the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and possibly the road you drive, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party has landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress are not able to agree on whether to continue, several states have not waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to switch to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles travelled.
Thousands of motorists have already embarked on these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS surveillance system, for an experimental ride.
This is absolutely essential for our nation.
“It’s not like we have a choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, the general manager of the Southern California Association of Governments, who predicts that the state will start recording the miles traveled by every Californian motorist by 2025.
There will be a change in how we pay these taxes.
The technology is there to do so.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country’s Highway Trust Fund, funded with taxes that Americans pay on the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can travel more than miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
“The gas tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
Its state recently installed trackers on 500 cars to test a mile payment system.
“This turns out to be the most logical long-term alternative,” he said.
Wonks calls this a mileage usage charge.
It is not surprising that the idea appeals to city liberals, as taxes could be used to change driving habits in ways that reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the state’s ambitious climate warming laws.
But Representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), chairman of the House Committee on Transport, said that he also considered it the most viable long-term alternative.
Free market supporters of the Reason Foundation also appreciate the idea of getting drivers to pay the mile.
“It’s not just a tax smuggling into a big black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of politics at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits that are provided to them.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Secretary of Transportation who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go in the path of payment to the mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have covered about 10,000 cars.
But the House presidency killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to work or to the city.
Several states and major cities, however, are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to lead the most important experience in the country.
These drivers will soon pay the state mileage instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is trying a test on a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the U.S. east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida) is studying how it could implement the change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their car with an appliance, drivers were worried that the government might follow their slightest facts and gestures.
“The concerns about Big Brother and that sort of thing are a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategic performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
From the start of the test, ACLU Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged location devices.”
There is no need to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people’s daily journeys and arrivals.
Nevada is one of the few states that are now trying to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car drives, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
Research into this technology has led some state agencies to use a small California startup called True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to help motorists who pay taxes to the states.
It was looking to break into the emerging car insurance market, in which drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices she’s testing have liked the big-axis planners because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, uploaded periodically by modem.
“People will be more inclined to do that if you don’t record their speed and locate them,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are far less expensive ways and far less intrusive ways to proceed.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering drivers different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They may still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles traveled by all state residents.
Other states hope to sell the concept to distrustful citizens by allowing the devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transportation officials are looking to develop a taxation device that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide “pay-to-drive” insurance, and create a set of real-time speed data from other drivers that drivers could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Automobilists would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits the system offers them,” said a document on urban planning.
However, some transport planners are wondering if the whole debate about mileage payment is not just a huge diversion.
At the San Francisco Bay Area Metropolitan Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very simply manage the Highway Trust Fund’s bankruptcy by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional one-off or annual tax could be imposed on hybrid vehicle drivers and others whose vehicles do not consume much gasoline, so each pays its fair share.
“There’s no need to resort to radical surgery when you just need aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, the commission’s director of legislation and public affairs.
