Ukraine Is Approaching Bankruptcy
The rating agency Standard & Poor's on Friday lowered Ukraine's credit rating, questioning the ability of the former Soviet republic, in recession for more than a year, to face its financial obligations.
The rating of the country's public debt securities goes to "B-", sinking into the category of speculative investments.
It is accompanied by a negative outlook, with S&P seeing at least one in three chance that it will be downgraded again within a year.
“It is less and less likely that the government’s strategy will guarantee enough foreign currencies to meet its high external financing needs,” the agency said.
The agency notes that Ukraine’s foreign exchange reserves fell by 26% between September 2012 and September 2013 and predicts that the trend will continue.
This complicates the repayment of credits taken abroad.
These reserves, which the authorities massively use to support the local currency, the hryvnia, are collapsing, the agency is increasingly likely to see a devaluation, which would inflate its external debt.
Kiev also needs liquidity to settle its gas imports to Russia, which accuses it of not paying an invoice of $882 million.
This announcement is bad news for the Ukrainian government in a period of intense tensions with its Russian neighbour, angry at Kiev’s willingness to sign an association agreement with the EU at the end of November.
It was made public the day after the publication of official statistics showing that the country’s economy had suffered its fifth quarter of contraction between July and September.
Its debt, still relatively modest, has exploded in recent years and S&P estimates it to be 33.5% of GDP, compared with less than 10% before the 2008-2009 crisis.
The country, which has a budget deficit, has been demanding assistance from the International Monetary Fund for months, which in 2010 granted it a credit of $15.3 billion and has so far only unlocked $3.4 billion.
But the Fund refuses to pay any new tranche until the country has adopted unpopular reforms to reduce its deficit, including by raising gas prices to the population.
Following an unsuccessful new mission to the country, the IMF found this week that "severe external financing needs" were "a vulnerability", while also "signs of economic improvement".
However, for economist Oleksandr Joloud of the Centre for Political Studies, "there is no expectation of improvement in the short term".
“There is little hope that unpopular reforms will be launched in a pre-election year,” the expert said, according to AFP.
