The United States has sometimes gone "too far" in terms of espionage, admitted Secretary of State John Kerry, in Washington's first confession in full controversy with Europe about the massive collection of data by the National Security Agency (NSA).
After ten days of scandal, revelations and denials between the United States and its European allies, it is the first time a U.S. government official has explicitly admitted controversial practices in the NSA’s interception of communications and data in Europe.
"In some cases, I concede to you, as the president has done, some of these actions have gone too far and we will make sure that it doesn't happen again in the future," Kerry said at a conference in London that he attended since Washington on October 31.
In his retransmitted speech, in the presence of his British counterpart William Hague, the head of the U.S. diplomacy has long justified intelligence and information gathering practices by the necessary counter-terrorism and prevention of possible attacks.
Invoking the attacks of 11 September 2001, the attacks of Madrid in March 2004 and those of London in July 2005, John Kerry assured that the U.S. authorities had since defunct numerous project attacks, thanks to the interception of communications and the collection of information.
“We have actually prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered, because we were able to be aware in advance of these projects,” the head of U.S. diplomacy said.
And, John Kerry said to the Europeans, “I assure you that in this process innocent people have not been deceived.”
But we're trying to gather information.
"And yes, in some cases, it went too far inappropriately," the secretary of state, who had already expressed himself on this international scandal during a tour last week in Paris, London and Rome, admitted.
He assured on Thursday night that President Obama was "determined to try to clarify and that he was re-examining these practices so that no one felt wrong."
But the controversy between Americans and Europeans continued to swell this week with new revelations in the press.
According to the Washington Post, the NSA was intercepting data from hundreds of millions of Google and Yahoo users.
The newspaper, citing documents obtained from former NSA consultant Edward Snowden, claims that the program dubbed "MUSCULAR", and conducted with the NSA's British counterpart, the GCHQ, allows these two agencies to retrieve data from the fibers used by the giants.
According to one of the documents, some 181 million items had been collected in January alone, ranging from metadata on emails, text items, or audio or video documents.
These interceptions would take place outside the United States.
But Yahoo and Google have denied any connection to these practices.
For the past ten days, several major newspapers in France, Germany, Spain and Italy have revealed that the NSA has intercepted massively data and communications from U.S. allies and their leaders, including German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Faced with the anger of European states and while leaks in the U.S. press claimed that the U.S. president was not aware of such hearings, Barack Obama refused to comment on it, invoking national security.
On the other hand, the boss of the powerful NSA, General Keith Alexander, denied that his intelligence agency had captured tens of millions of communications from European citizens.
He even referred the bullet to the European intelligence services that would have seized these communications, before providing them to the NSA.
This would be about "military operations" in countries where these NATO allies are cooperating with the United States and it would not be aimed at Europe at all, General Alexander said.
And the controversy spread on Friday to Asia.
