YouGov interviewed more than 1,000 business leaders, globally representative of all sizes of companies, sectors and regions in the UK.
The findings of the investigation will be a surprise for many.
We found that the vast majority of companies are now looking to export outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernising and developing while EU states are stagnating.
They want to see the government prioritize new trade ties with countries such as China, India and Brazil rather than getting caught up in the long and difficult process of reforming European institutional arcanas.
When asked for their opinion on specific policy points – ranging from monopoly regulation to product laws – the majority of business leaders think that control of these key skills should return to Westminster.
The single market has caused general dissatisfaction, with companies saying that the cost of the Brussels Regulation is disproportionate to the benefits it has to be part of the European trade area – 40% of the large companies, traditionally the most pro-European, even agree.
Lastly, and more importantly, our survey of business leaders revealed that a large majority wanted to see Britain pursue initiatives to change the treaty and develop a trade-based relationship with the EU, not politics.
This conclusion, which is found in all large groups and companies of all sizes, shows that the business world is insisting on a “significant change” that brings power back to the UK.
The stakes are high – succeeding to change the treaty and better represent Britain’s interests would see a 16% turnout in favour of retaining the country in the EU during a referendum.
The prime minister should not doubt a single moment: this survey shows that British companies support this plan to renegotiate the terms of Britain’s accession to the EU.
It also shows that companies hope that the renegotiation will represent a significant change in the current balance of power in favor of a return to the hands of the United Kingdom.
It is possible, and increasingly necessary, to better represent the interests of British companies, as the euro area is committed to a closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be employment and growth in the UK, and, as the findings of our survey show, for businesses this means re-focusing on trade and a fundamental change in the Brussels regulatory approach.
