How Biometrics Invaded Our Lives
Finished the passwords to type to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French, or Japanese researchers are predicting a future where we will be recognized by biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy general manager of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person performing transactions in a world as transversal and transnational as the Internet.
Organizations dedicated to the protection of privacy confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but are concerned about it.
In 2011 alone and in France, the National Commission for Informatics and Freedoms authorized 774 fingerprint, hand shape or hand venous network recognition systems in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will build on new techniques, which will enable new services to be provided to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most widely used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contours, and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
“For example, some people who work with concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable,” says Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity domain at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand assume a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - one cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a drawback: sometimes the procedure needs to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted for some 20 years on other approaches, such as facial recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increased accuracy of the sensors and the computational capacity of the computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold over the past five years, according to Cyrille Bataller, Director of Accenture’s R&D Labs in Europe.
With our help, the UK and Holland have deployed automatic border crossings using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
A unique and infallible marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
“In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data,” says Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers the judicial police services a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in an hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing a person among others) and authentication (ensure that the person is who they claim to be).
The identification thus far concerned the issue of identity papers: biometric elements (prints, photo, iris) must be confronted with the information that the State has on all citizens already registered.
This ensures that a person does not attempt to overwhelm someone else’s identity.
This comparison principle may have other applications.
NEC thus offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or store.
“We are retrieving the images from the surveillance cameras and comparing them to the photos of celebrities circulating freely on the Internet,” says Dany Nassif, head of commercial development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Another use: take a photo of a guy who is queuing in a store, track his progression through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially involved physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens, etc.) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, presence checks have been added.
“A biometric tip avoids the phenomenon of a friend pointing for another,” says Accenture’s Cyrille Bataller.
But, more and more, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from certain distributors by introducing his card and placing his hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the key of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoul<0xC3><0xAA>me by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and wholesalers: when paying in store with his bank card, the customer does not tap his code, but inserts his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
“If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in cash for thirty seconds less, it’s appreciable,” explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you bespoke options.
And finally, rest assured by highlighting the precautions taken to protect the databases.
“Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people’s identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which blocks if one tries to move it,” says Philippe Robin, Thales.
But, due to the lack of in-depth study, it is impossible to know if these speeches really convince users.
The specialists in the protection of privacy, they, continue to worry.
“The advances in facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras, and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me afraid of the worst: widespread surveillance,” said Andrew Patrick of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
