Scientists have just highlighted how the movements of a dog’s tail are related to its mood.
Previous studies had revealed that happy dogs moved their tail more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs moved their tail more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trente, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are involved in different ways in stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions.”
Here, we tried to see what it was like in other species.
He added that in humans, in dogs, the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the disordered tail movements of other dogs, the researchers tracked animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the animals’ heart rate and analyzed their behavior.
It will probably not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented dogs with films featuring other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factor – and we were able to traverse the tail movement and present it as going further left or right.”
When the animals saw a dog with no expression moving the tail to the right (from the dog’s point of view moving the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail diverting mainly to the left (again from the dog’s point of view moving the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know from experience the movements they should or shouldn’t worry about.
He added: “If you meet other dogs several times and you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react based on that experience.”
The researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a guest professor at the University of Bristol’s School of Veterinary Sciences, said it was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the dog species.
