A team of biologists led by the New York Wildlife Conservation Society have identified a new species of crustacean dolphin off Australia’s northern coast.
Thibaut Bouveroux, scientific missioner at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Marine Animals and Environments (OCEAMM) returns for L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identification of new species.
Is the discovery of this new species of humpback dolphin surprising to you?
That's good news, but I'm not particularly surprised.
While in the past, species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge in species classification sciences.
Moreover, it is not impossible for these advances in genetics and molecular biology to call into question the classification or affiliation of a species to a genus, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these classifications are being challenged due to advances in genetics.
In the same way, two very morphologically close species have been distinguished by genetics.
This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
About a decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific cubic dolphins and Atlantic cubic whales.
Recent analyses have made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is this an important discovery, as stated by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population was already known for a long time by researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only at this place.
Therefore, if a massive mortality problem caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture arises in the region, we may be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than the local extinction of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered depending on the number of individuals existing on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the possibility that it has to recover from neighboring stocks.
As for the Sousa chinensis species, whose population of the new discovered species came from, its stock has automatically become weaker, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This brewing of genes limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems favor genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It should be noted that the marine environment is the least well-known environment.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, rather than knowing what lives in the Marianne pit, just 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
We spend more money in the search for life on other planets than in marine research and it’s high time that this changes.
